Since information markets, in nature, offer an adaptive and  selforganized mechanism to aggregate opinions of market  participants, it is interesting to compare them with existing opinion pooling methods, to evaluate the performance of information markets from another perspective.
This paper contributes to the literature in two ways : ( 1 ) As an initial attempt to compare information markets with opinion pools of multiple experts , it leads to a better understanding of information markets and their promise as an alternative institution for obtaining accurate forecasts ; ( 2 ) In screening opinion pools to be used in the comparison 